posts.com: The best way to start learning to lucid dream is to maybe stay up a night or two until you get that kinda “dreaming while awake” feeling. The second you close your eyes you’ll probably get some REM visuals although you know you’re awake to an extent. You’ll still be delirious so may not pick it up at first but this is the point where you can learn to find “triggers” that will tell your brain that you are dreaming. Some will try to look for things they make up. I know in American Dad, Steve would notice a red ball and that would be his signal that he’s in a dream. For me it was reading signs/books/anything with written words. I noticed that when I was dreaming if I looked away from what I was reading and turned back, the words would change or appear as random shit. Then I’d instantly know I was in a dream. Your body will be in sleep paralysis at this point and this is the next thing you have to overcome. You need to remember that sleep paralysis exists and 1) don’t be afraid of it and cause anxiety that will wake you up and 2) remember that even though in your dream even though you will feel your muscle movements as your brain signals them, they won’t actually move outside the dream. It’s weird seeing your arm move up in the dream all while knowing it’s not moving on your sleeping body. You can actually feel things too because your brain will signal the feelings based off of your memory. For instance, you can feel certain fabrics due to your brains expectation of what they feel like. I’d recommend sleeping on your back because if you’re laying on an arm or leg you may subconsciously notice that your arm or leg is immobile and this will effect your lucid dream experience. From there you gotta learn to walk and move around. Your body is trying to say it isn’t moving to your brain, but you have to convince your unconscious mind that you are, at least in the dream. Sometimes you gotta be forceful about it.

Vertex painting for masks has been in use since before playstation was a thing. You see skyboxes and such in old games often being vertex painted.

Understanding the definition of ekklesia (and its alternate spelling ecclesia) is an important component of understanding the church. Ekklesia is a Greek word defined as “a called-out assembly or congregation.” Ekklesia is commonly translated as “church” in the New Testament. For example, Acts 11:26 says that “Barnabas and Saul met with the church [ekklesia]” in Antioch. And in 1 Corinthians 15:9 Paul says that he had persecuted the church [ekklesia] of God.” The “called-out assembly,” then, is a congregation of believers whom God has called out of the world and “into His wonderful light” (1 Peter 2:9). The Greek ekklesia is the basis for our English words ecclesiastical (“pertaining to the church”) and ecclesiology (“the study of doctrine concerning the church”).
